-- South African Stocks Fall, Snapping Three-Day Gain, Led by Anglo, Billiton
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-08T16:37:36Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-08/south-african-stocks-drop-snapping-3-days-of-gains-led-by-anglo-american.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  declined 67.48, or 0.2 percent, to 31,388.98,
snapping three days of gains, at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today:  Afrimat Ltd.  (AFT SJ), a cement and concrete supplier, rose
23 cents, or 6.9 percent, to 3.55 rand, the highest closing
price since November 2008. Net income for the first half to Aug.
31 advanced to 44.9 million rand ($6.5 million), from 42.1
million rand.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the second-largest company on
the Johannesburg bourse, dropped 4.85 rand, or 1.5 percent, to
328.64 rand, snapping three days of gains. Nickel, tin, zinc and
lead prices fell in London.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the
world’s largest mining company, retreated 1.20 rand, or 0.5
percent, to 267.80 rand.  Cadiz Holdings Ltd.  (CDZ SJ), a financial services holding
company, slipped the most since April 1, dropping 20 cents, or
5.6 percent, to 3.40 rand. The company reported first-half net
income declined 25 percent to 26.9 million rand.  Impala Platinum Holdings  (IMP SJ), the world’s second-
largest platinum producer, lost 99 cents, or 0.5 percent, to 209
rand, snapping two days of advances. Platinum declined as much
as 0.9 percent to $1,749.35 an ounce.  Pick n Pay Stores Ltd.  (PIK SJ), a grocery retailer,
increased for the 13th consecutive trading day, gaining 49
cents, or 1 percent, to 49.30 rand. That’s the longest streak of
gains since August 1990 when Bloomberg started compiling the
data. The company said it will open four stores in Maputo,
Mozambique, by the end of 2011.  Royal Bafokeng Platinum Ltd.  (RBP SJ), the platinum
producer known as RBPlat, rose 4.40 rand, or 7.27 percent, to
64.90 rand. RBPlat, which raised 2.97 billion rand, or 60.50
rand a share in a bookbuild before the stock started trading
today, said it may cut the cost of its Styldrift project by 1
billion rand from 11.8 billion rand, Business Day reported.  Sappi Ltd.  (SAP SJ) , the world’s largest producer of
glossy magazine paper, climbed 1.89 rand, or 5.7 percent, to
35.24 rand. The company reported that earnings per share were 16
cents, compared with a loss of 20 cents per share a year
earlier.  Vodacom Group Ltd.  (VOD SJ), South Africa’s largest mobile-
phone operator, gained 69 cents, or 1 percent, to 68.49 rand.
The company said first-half profit to September surged to 4.42
billion rand, from 61 million rand a year earlier. The group
said it has an increased appetite for acquisitions in Africa.
 MTN Group Ltd.  (MTN SJ), the continent’s biggest provider of
mobile telephone services, lost 1.46 rand, or 1.1 percent, to
127.20 rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
